While you have a five course meal, you can select any combination of five dishes from the appetizers, seafood, meat, cheese, and desserts- you don't have to select one from each category! Definitely worth a trip if you're looking for an extremely nice meal out in San Francisco.

Gary Danko is one of my top fine dining experiences! The food, the service, and the atmosphere is always top notch. It's pricier than your average restaurant, but such a good deal considering the gourmet food and excellent service you get. This is truly one of my top fine dining experiences. I've been here just twice so far but both times have been wonderful. The eats: Anchovies and Parmigiano-Reggiano Risotto with Lobster was SOOO delicious. Everyone who ordered this loved it.. the portion was good too. When I went the second time, I tried the seared foie gras everyone was raving about.. it was really excellent. Now I regret the first time when I didn't order it! They have a wide variety of items to get and the best part is, you can pick and choose from whatever category you like. The Service: Everyone is friendly, your glass is always full, whenever you leave your seat you'll always return to a nicely folded napkin with everything put in it's place. Clean utensils are served with each plate and they're always ready to serve you. Outstanding service. Other tips: If you can find street parking, take it! Valet runs you $10 plus tip. I've heard stories of people booking MONTHS in advance for Gary Danko. If you have a super special occasion to celebrate, put that into consideration. Otherwise, whenever I know I'll be in town, I ask to be put on the waiting list just a few days prior to the day I want. They typically have some canceled reservations and I'm always happy to take those rather than wait months. All and all, Gary Danko is pretty freaking fantastic. I always jump at making a stop here when I'm in town and if you get a chance, definitely get acquainted with Gary Danko's restaurant.

Private birthday lunch for my friend Carla :) Lovely dining room, huge floral arrangements in keeping with the birthday girl's "Spring Chic" theme. As we waited for the others to arrive, we were served rose champagne and buckwheat blinis with creme fraiche, smoked salmon, and caviar. You HAVE to pop the entire thing in your mouth (that's what he said, ha)...because that's when the magical flavor explosion happens. Once seated, we were given an amuse bouche- a vegetable soup of sorts, it was delicious and creamy. The seared foie gras they served next made sweet love to my tastebuds. My groans of pleasure must have been inappropriate, but I'm pretty sure they were drowned out by the collective sighs of my fellow diners. The slightly sweet white wine paired with it was perfecto. The lobster salad's combination of pear, mango, avocado, cashews with a lime-cilantro sauce was a definite win. It was rich but very refreshing at the same time. Roast filet of beef was tender, juicy, and very flavorful. The cheese platter made my stomach smile - 4 different cheeses (the only name I remember is "Demon du Midi," the Afternoon Demon)- the walnut raisin bread was killer! Dessert was warm Louisiana butter cake with apples and vanilla ice cream. Slightly crispy and caramelized on the outside, moist and buttery on the inside. As I savored each bite, I found myself wishing that my dessert could have the regenerative capabilities of a starfish (in hyper-speed, of course). Coffee was served with mignardises - these excellent miniature sweets should star in "Honey I Shrank the Dessert." From beginning to end, service was impeccable. After they helped me with my coat, they sent me off with a copy of the menu signed by Mr. Danko and a little wrapped "breakfast cake." How can this be anything less than a five??? Maybe if I had suffered multiple paper cuts on my tongue from stuffing envelopes the night before? Five stars plus five snaps in a circle. Btw, I cheated - I had the "morning-after cake" that night. Amazing banana cake with a creme filling. Devoured.every.last.crumb. Telling me to save it for breakfast is akin to telling someone to keep their eyes open when they sneeze.

Is Gary Danko the best restaurant in San Francisco? Now, I'm a believer. I came here for my gf's mom's birthday celebration and TRUST ME, it does not disappoint. I ordered a 3 item course without dessert. Seriously, i was a sucker for their sea food menu. I started with the Lobster Salad. The lime cilantro remoulade Seriously brought the dish together. That sauce combined with the freshness of the mango and the avocado was soooo good. AND with a huge piece of fresh super sweet lobster, what more can you ask for? Next i had the Seared Sea Scallops. I'm a huge fan of scallops, and believe me, those were THE BEST sea scallops I've ever tried. The sear on the scallops was PERFECT. Super tender on the inside with an amazing crunch on the outside. And with the basil puree i think it was? YUM. I just wanted more of it! I could have eaten hundreds of those Scallops. I finished off with the Coconut Curry, because it had lobster, calamari and SCALLOPS, again. So good. My only negative comment about this dish is the amount of lemon grass used. I wanted to taste more of the coconut flavor, but the amount of lemon grass chunks kind of overpowered the taste of the dish. It was very good nevertheless :) I finished off by sharing a cheese plate. My biggest compliment goes to the staff. Man, these guys sure know how to run their restaurant. Impeccable service and presentation!!! And our waiter, we got along so well and he REALLY knew his cheeses. SERIOUSLY. There were 15 of them and he knew the history and the distinct tastes of all of them!!! It was amazing. The double cream brie and the triple cream blue were pretty tasty, but there is one cheese on there that is a MUST TRY. I forgot the name of it, but it was orange colored. It was paprika spiced and it had a nutty flavor to it. It's my new favorite cheese :) We got some free desserts for the birthday occasion, including a lemon panna cotta with an assortment of little gourmet cookies. I tried the panna cotta and it was a perfect end to a meal. Not to rich with a sweet, tart flavor to it. So if it's your birthday or another special occasion.....this is the perfect place to celebrate! I live in southern California and I would actually consider flying up to Gary Danko for my birthday dinner. No joke. It's that good. It's something to experience atleast one in your life :D

When we sat down at our table, I noticed our seating arrangement was different. I normally like to sit across and facing my date rather then sitting next to them. My first impression of the meal was it's OK. I was going into it thinking since this place had good reviews expecting to be amazed. Our servers kept getting our orders mixed up. One complaint was they would give my Fiancé my dishes and hers to me. Not really a big issue, but if you are considered a high class restaurant, I would assume you would pay attention to the details. The ambiance was nice, lowly dim lights. But like I mentioned earlier, the way we were seated, our view was of others at their tables. If I were to compare Alexanders to Gary Danko, I would choose Alexanders. If you love cheese, they do give you a variety of choices on cheese. The server would push out a cart filled with a different variety. I do like cheese but it was a bit weird for me to just sample different cheese as part of my dining experience. My experience at Gary Danko wasn't bad, but for the amount that we paid for, not sure if I would return.

Trying to look for a fancy place that will accommodate your company party of 20 can sometimes be hard, but I guess I lucked out when Gary Danko told me that they couldn't help us for dinner but could set up a private lunch for us last Saturday (4/13/2013)! The place has a pretty modern and classy look about it, but I could do without the fake butterflies. It made the place feel cheap and tacky, which is far from what it actually was. The minute we walked in they immediately asked if we wanted a refreshing beverage or if we wanted to check in our coats so that we would feel more at ease and comfortable while we waited for the rest of our party to arrive. We decided to go with a 4 course meal with individual wine pairings: Amouse Bouche - Carrot with Curry Powder Soup ~Curry wasn't overpowering and pretty good to start off. Almost reminded me of butternut squash soup. 1st Course (Appetizer) - Risotto with Dungeness Crab, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms and Peas Wine Pairing - Franz Hirtzberger Grüner Veltliner, Rotes Tor, Smaragd, Wachau, Austria 2009 ~Not too heavy and packed with seafood goodness and flavor! 2nd Course - Roast Main Lobster with Potato Puree, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon Wine Pairing - Beauregard Vineyards Chardonnay, Ben Lomond Mountain, Santa Cruz Mountains, California 2011 ~I loved the potato puree because I feel like mashed potatoes would have put me over the edge before I could get to the next course. It had a nice light and creamy texture to it. 3rd Course - Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Shallot Marmalade and Bordelaise Butter Wine Pairing - Jordan Cabernet Sauvignon, Alexander Valley, California 2008 ~My beef was cooked to medium rare perfection! It was just so deliciously tender and the flavors were really harmonious. Not only that, but the sauvignon was the perfect pairing, because it was actually smooth and sweet. (And I'm by no means a wine aficionado) 4th Course (DESSERT) - Baked Chocolate Souffle with 2 Sauces (Caramelized Sauce and Belgian Chocolate Sauce Wine Pairing - M. Chapoutier Banyuls, Vin Doux Naturel, Languedoc-Roussillon, France 2010 ~Dessert Connoisseurs beware of this chocolate fluffy cloud-like goodness they call souffle! It was so good, I could have had like 2 more! This place just kept giving too cause by the time we left, we were given personalized menus that were signed by Gary Danko himself! Along with that, we were also given complimentary home-made banana bread cakes in gold wrapping as favors. Everything is just delectable. After this experience alone, I highly recommend this place because the service is superb and pretty professional. Constantly asking you questions to make sure that you are fully accommodated and your water glass is always filled to the brim. They even splash proof it with a towel as they pour! Allergies? No problem, they'll offer you a full list of alternative things they can provide you with.

    Gary Danko is one of my top fine dining experiences!

    The food, the service, and the atmosphere is always top notch.  It's pricier than your average restaurant, but such a good deal considering the gourmet food and excellent service you get.  This is truly one of my top fine dining experiences. I've been here just twice so far but both times have been wonderful.

    The eats:
    Anchovies and Parmigiano-Reggiano Risotto with Lobster was SOOO delicious.  Everyone who ordered this loved it.. the portion was good too.  When I went the second time, I tried the seared foie gras everyone was raving about.. it was really excellent. Now I regret the first time when I didn't order it!  They have a wide variety of items to get and the best part is, you can pick and choose from whatever category you like.  The food is spectacular... no matter what you order, it will be made with high quality ingredients and very nicely prepared.  There are just too many items on the menu to comment on!

    The Service:
    Everyone is friendly, your glass is always full, whenever you leave your seat you'll always return to a nicely folded napkin with everything put in it's place.  Clean utensils are served with each plate and they're always ready to serve you.  Outstanding service.  

    Other tips:
    If you can find street parking, take it! Valet runs you $10 plus tip.  I've heard stories of people booking MONTHS in advance for Gary Danko.  If you have a super special occasion to celebrate, put that into consideration.  Otherwise, whenever I know I'll be in town, I ask to be put on the waiting list just a few days prior to the day I want.  They typically have some canceled reservations and I'm always happy to take those rather than wait months.

    All and all, Gary Danko is pretty freaking fantastic.  I always jump at making a stop here when I'm in town and if you get a chance, definitely get acquainted with Gary Danko's restaurant.

    3/28/2011

    Private birthday lunch for my friend Carla :)

    Lovely dining room, huge floral arrangements in keeping with the birthday girl's "Spring Chic" theme.  As we waited for the others to arrive, we were served rose champagne and buckwheat blinis with creme fraiche, smoked salmon, and caviar.  You HAVE to pop the entire thing in your mouth (that's what he said, ha)...because that's when the magical flavor explosion happens.

    Once seated, we were given an amuse bouche- a vegetable soup of sorts, it was delicious and creamy.

    The seared foie gras they served next made sweet love to my tastebuds.  My groans of pleasure must have been inappropriate, but I'm pretty sure they were drowned out by the collective sighs of my fellow diners.  The slightly sweet white wine paired with it was perfecto.

    The lobster salad's combination of pear, mango, avocado, cashews with a lime-cilantro sauce was a definite win.  It was rich but very refreshing at the same time.

    Roast filet of beef was tender, juicy, and very flavorful.

    The cheese platter made my stomach smile - 4 different cheeses (the only name I remember is "Demon du Midi," the Afternoon Demon)- the  walnut raisin bread was killer!

    Dessert was warm Louisiana butter cake with apples and vanilla ice cream.  Slightly crispy and caramelized on the outside, moist and buttery on the inside.  As I savored each bite, I found myself wishing that my dessert could have the regenerative capabilities of a starfish (in hyper-speed, of course).

    Coffee was served with mignardises - these excellent miniature sweets should star in "Honey I Shrank the Dessert."  

    From beginning to end, service was impeccable.  After they helped me with my coat, they sent me off with a copy of the menu signed by Mr. Danko and a little wrapped "breakfast cake."

    How can this be anything less than a five??? Maybe if I had suffered multiple paper cuts on my tongue from stuffing envelopes the night before?  Five stars plus five snaps in a circle.

    Btw, I cheated - I had the "morning-after cake" that night.  Amazing banana cake with a creme filling.  Devoured.every.last.crumb.  Telling me to save it for breakfast is akin to telling someone to keep their eyes open when they sneeze.

    Is Gary Danko the best restaurant in San Francisco? Now, I'm a believer.
    I came here for my gf's mom's birthday celebration and TRUST ME, it does not disappoint.
    I ordered a 3 item course without dessert. Seriously, i was a sucker for their sea food menu.

    I started with the Lobster Salad. The lime cilantro remoulade Seriously brought the dish together. That sauce combined with the freshness of the mango and the avocado was soooo good. AND with a huge piece of fresh super sweet lobster, what more can you ask for?

    Next i had the Seared Sea Scallops. I'm a huge fan of scallops, and believe me, those were THE BEST sea scallops I've ever tried. The sear on the scallops was PERFECT. Super tender on the inside with an amazing crunch on the outside. And with the basil puree i think it was? YUM. I just wanted more of it! I could have eaten hundreds of those Scallops.

    I finished off with the Coconut Curry, because it had lobster, calamari and SCALLOPS, again. So good. My only negative comment  about this dish is the amount of lemon grass used. I wanted to taste more of the coconut flavor, but the amount of lemon grass chunks kind of overpowered the taste of the dish. It was very good nevertheless :)

    I finished off by sharing a cheese plate. My biggest compliment goes to the staff. Man, these guys sure know how to run their restaurant. Impeccable service and presentation!!! And our waiter, we got along so well and he REALLY knew his cheeses. SERIOUSLY. There were 15 of them and he knew the history and the distinct tastes of all of them!!! It was amazing. The double cream brie and the triple cream blue were pretty tasty, but there is one cheese on there that is a MUST TRY. I forgot the name of it, but it was orange colored. It was paprika spiced and it had a nutty flavor to it. It's my new favorite cheese :)

    We got some free desserts for the birthday occasion, including a lemon panna cotta with an assortment of little gourmet cookies. I tried the panna cotta and it was a perfect end to a meal. Not to rich with a sweet, tart flavor to it. So if it's your birthday or another special occasion.....this is the perfect place to celebrate!

    I live in southern California and I would actually consider flying up to Gary Danko for my birthday dinner. No joke. It's that good. It's something to experience atleast one in your life :D

    4/22/2013

    Trying to look for a fancy place that will accommodate your company party of 20 can sometimes be hard, but I guess I lucked out when Gary Danko told me that they couldn't help us for dinner but could set up a private lunch for us last Saturday (4/13/2013)!

    The place has a pretty modern and classy look about it, but I could do without the fake butterflies. It made the place feel cheap and tacky, which is far from what it actually was. The minute we walked in they immediately asked if we wanted a refreshing beverage or if we wanted to check in our coats so that we would feel more at ease and comfortable while we waited for the rest of our party to arrive.

    We decided to go with a 4 course meal with individual wine pairings:

    Amouse Bouche - Carrot with Curry Powder Soup
    ~Curry wasn't overpowering and pretty good to start off. Almost reminded me of butternut squash soup.

    1st Course (Appetizer) - Risotto with Dungeness Crab, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms and Peas
    Wine Pairing - Franz Hirtzberger Grüner Veltliner, Rotes Tor, Smaragd, Wachau, Austria 2009
    ~Not too heavy and packed with seafood goodness and flavor!

    2nd Course - Roast Main Lobster with Potato Puree, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon
    Wine Pairing - Beauregard Vineyards Chardonnay, Ben Lomond Mountain, Santa Cruz Mountains, California 2011
    ~I loved the potato puree because I feel like mashed potatoes would have put me over the edge before I could get to the next course. It had a nice light and creamy texture to it.

    3rd Course - Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Shallot Marmalade and Bordelaise Butter
    Wine Pairing - Jordan Cabernet Sauvignon, Alexander Valley, California 2008
    ~My beef was cooked to medium rare perfection! It was just so deliciously tender and the flavors were really harmonious. Not only that, but the sauvignon was the perfect pairing, because it was actually smooth and sweet. (And I'm by no means a wine aficionado)

    4th Course (DESSERT) - Baked Chocolate Souffle with 2 Sauces (Caramelized Sauce and Belgian Chocolate Sauce
    Wine Pairing - M. Chapoutier Banyuls, Vin Doux Naturel, Languedoc-Roussillon, France 2010
    ~Dessert Connoisseurs beware of this chocolate fluffy cloud-like goodness they call souffle! It was so good, I could have had like 2 more!

    This place just kept giving too cause by the time we left, we were given personalized menus that were signed by Gary Danko himself! Along with that, we were also given complimentary home-made banana bread cakes in gold wrapping as favors. Everything is just delectable.

    After this experience alone, I highly recommend this place because the service is superb and pretty professional. Constantly asking you questions to make sure that you are fully accommodated and your water glass is always filled to the brim. They even splash proof it with a towel as they pour! Allergies? No problem, they'll offer you a full list of alternative things they can provide you with.
